`Queue.unbounded` never blocks the producer — if the consumer stalls, memory grows without bound. `Queue.bounded(n)` blocks `Queue.offer` once the buffer is full, turning the queue into a backpressure signal: a fast producer automatically slows down to match a slow consumer. Use bounded whenever the upstream is driven by something you can't pause (a network socket, a file reader) and you want predictable memory use.

