`Effect.all({ concurrency: N })` bounds concurrency *within a single* `Effect.all` call — two back-to-back calls can each run N effects in parallel (2×N in flight during the overlap, if they're forked). A `Semaphore` is a shared limiter: every effect that acquires a permit counts against the same budget, so the global cap holds across calls, fibers, and even across unrelated pipelines that share the semaphore handle.

```typescript
import { Effect } from "effect";

declare const hit: (url: string) => Effect.Effect<number>;

export const program: Effect.Effect<ReadonlyArray<number>> = Effect.gen(function* () {
  const sem = yield* Effect.makeSemaphore(2); // global cap of 2 across both batches.

  const batchA = Effect.all(
    ["a1", "a2", "a3"].map((u) => sem.withPermits(1)(hit(u))),
    { concurrency: "unbounded" },
  );
  const batchB = Effect.all(
    ["b1", "b2", "b3"].map((u) => sem.withPermits(1)(hit(u))),
    { concurrency: "unbounded" },
  );

  const [a, b] = yield* Effect.all([batchA, batchB], { concurrency: "unbounded" });
  return [...a, ...b];
});
```

